body:
Hi, i think it can be solved this way, while maintaining backward compatibility.

```php
public static function convertExceptionToError($exception)
{
    if (PHP_VERSION_ID >= 80400) {
        $exceptionMessage = static::convertExceptionToString($exception);

        Yii::error($exceptionMessage, 'E_USER_ERROR');

        if (PHP_SAPI !== 'cli') {
            echo $exceptionMessage;
        } else {
            fwrite(STDERR, $exceptionMessage . PHP_EOL);
        }

        exit(1);
    } else {
        trigger_error(static::convertExceptionToString($exception), E_USER_ERROR);
    }
}
```

@samdark @mtangoo @bizley @rob006 @schmunk42 @xepozz

Yes, If it is used only in two `to_string()`, but the deprecation is only in `PHP` `8.4`, so it would make sense, not to deprecate the method, and only call it if it is `PHP` < `8.4`, so we would not do BC.

```php
public function __toString()
{
    // __toString cannot throw exception
    // use trigger_error to bypass this limitation
    try {
        return $this->toString();
    } catch (\Throwable $e) {
        if (PHP_VERSION_ID < 80400) {
            trigger_error(ErrorHandler::convertExceptionToString($e), E_USER_ERROR);

            return '';
        }

        throw $e;
    }
}
````

Or throw exception in `convertExceptionToError()` without depreciating the method..
